04272nam a22006495i 9780823237555DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232375557 a10.1515/97808232375552doi  a(DE-B1597)555421  a(OCoLC)1098638122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB2430.D484bN32 2008eb 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a1942221 aNaas, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDerrida From Now On /cMichael Naas. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations of Works by Jacques Derrida -- tIntroduction. Bénédictions-''traces in the history of the French language'' -- t1. Alors, qui êtes-vous? -- t2. Analogy and Anagram -- t3. Derrida's Laïcité -- t4. A Last Call for ''Europe'' -- t5. Derrida's America -- t6. Derrida at the Wheel -- t7. ''One Nation . . . Indivisible'' -- t8. Autonomy, Autoimmunity, and the Stretch Limo -- t9. History's Remains -- t10. Comme si, comme ça -- t11. Lifelines -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWritten in the wake of Jacques Derrida's death in 2004, Derrida From Now On attempts both to do justice to the memory of Derrida and to demonstrate the continuing significance of his work for contemporary philosophy and literary theory. If Derrida's thought is to remain relevant for us today, it must be at once understood in its original context and uprooted and transplanted elsewhere. Michael Naas thus begins with an analysis of Derrida's attachment to the French language, to Europe, and to European secular thought, before turning to Derrida's long engagement with the American context and to the ways in which deconstruction allows us to rethink the history, identity, and promise of post-9/11 America. Taking as its point of departure several of Derrida's later works (from "Faith and Knowledge" and The Work of Mourning to Rogues and Learning to Live Finally), the book demonstrates how Derrida's analyses of the phantasms of sovereignty, the essential autoimmunity of democracy or religion, or the impossible mourning of the nation-state can help us to understand what is happening today in American culture, literature, and politics. Though Derrida's thought has always lived on only by being translated elsewhere, his disappearance will have driven home this necessity with a new force and an unprecedented urgency. Derrida From Now On is an effect of this force and an attempt to respond to this urgency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823237555zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823237555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823237555.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK